SIMPLE: fee
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fee
<hw>Fee</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fe</ets>,
<ets>feh</ets>, <ets>feoh</ets>, cattle, property, money, fief, AS.
<ets>feoh</ets> cattle, property, money; the senses of ⟦ldquo⟧property,
money,⟦rdquo⟧ arising from cattle being used in early times as a medium
of exchange or payment, property chiefly consisting of cattle; akin to
OS. <ets>fehu</ets> cattle, property, D. <ets>vee</ets> cattle, OHG.
<ets>fihu</ets>, <ets>fehu</ets>, G. <ets>vieh</ets>, Icel.
<ets>f⟦emac⟧</ets> cattle, property, money, Goth.
<ets>fa⟦iacute⟧hu</ets>, L. <ets>pecus</ets> cattle, <ets>pecunia</ets>
property, money, Skr. <ets>pa⟦cced⟧u</ets> cattle, perh. orig., ⟦ldquo⟧a
fastened or tethered animal,⟦rdquo⟧ from a root signifying <ets>to
bind</ets>, and perh. akin to E. <ets>fang</ets>, <ets>fair</ets>, a.;
cf. OF. <ets>fie</ets>, <ets>flu</ets>, <ets>feu</ets>, <ets>fleu</ets>,
<ets>fief</ets>, F. <ets>fief</ets>, from German, of the same origin.
the sense <ets>fief</ets> is due to the French. ⟦root⟧249. Cf.
<er>Feud</er>, <er>Fief</er>, <er>Fellow</er>,
<er>Pecuniary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>property; possession;
tenure.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Laden with rich <xex>fee</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Once did she hold the gorgeous East in <qex>fee</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Reward or compensation for services rendered or to
be rendered; especially, payment for professional services, of optional
amount, or fixed by custom or laws; charge; pay; perquisite; <as>as, the
<ex>fees</ex> of lawyers and physicians; the <ex>fees</ex> of office;
clerk's <ex>fees</ex>; sheriff's <ex>fees</ex>; marriage <ex>fees</ex>,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To plead for love deserves more <qex>fee</qex> than hate.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Feud. Law)</fld> <def>A right to the use of a
superior's land, as a stipend for services to be performed; also, the
land so held; a fief.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>An estate of inheritance
supposed to be held either mediately or immediately from the sovereign,
and absolutely vested in the owner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ All the land in England, except the crown land, is of
this kind. An <xex>absolute fee</xex>, or <xex>fee simple</xex>, is land
which a man holds to himself and his heirs forever, who are called
<xex>tenants in fee simple</xex>. In modern writers, by <xex>fee</xex>
is usually meant <xex>fee simple</xex>. A <xex>limited fee</xex> may be
a <xex>qualified</xex> or <xex>base fee</xex>, which ceases with the
existence of certain conditions; or a <xex>conditional fee</xex>, or
<xex>fee tail</xex>, which is limited to particular heirs.</note>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Amer. Law)</fld> <def>An estate of inheritance
belonging to the owner, and transmissible to his heirs, absolutely and
simply, without condition attached to the tenure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Fee estate</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>land or
tenements held in fee in consideration or some acknowledgment or service
rendered to the lord.</cd> -- <col><b>Fee farm</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>land held of another in fee, in consideration of
an annual rent, without homage, fealty, or any other service than that
mentioned in the feoffment; an estate in fee simple, subject to a
perpetual rent.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au> -- <col><b>Fee farm
rent</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>a perpetual rent reserved upon
a conveyance in fee simple.</cd> -- <col><b>Fee fund</b></col>
<fld>(Scot. Law)</fld>, <cd>certain court dues out of which the clerks
and other court officers are paid.</cd> -- <col><b>Fee simple</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>an absolute fee; a fee without conditions or
limits.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Buy the <qex>fee simple</qex> of my life for an hour and a
quarter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>Fee tail</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>an estate of
inheritance, limited and restrained to some particular heirs.</cd>
<au>Burill.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Fee</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fee
<hw>Fee</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Feed</conjf> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Feeing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To reward for services
performed, or to be performed; to recompense; to hire or keep in hire;
hence, to bribe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The patient . . . <qex>fees</qex> the doctor.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There's not a one of them but in his house⟦br⟧
I keep a servant <qex>feed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feeble</ent>⟦br⟧
